ormal_709f56dcbe9246709dbad7f88dfbdcd8.jpg Image] || 1933 || [[Venetian Lagoon]]<br>{{coord|45|25|13.17|N|12|21|46.76|E}} || Fl (2) R 10s. || {{convert|7|m|ft}} || 11548 || E2492 || 5\n|- \n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lists of lighthouses and lightvessels]]\n* [[Marina Militare]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lighthouses in Italy}}\n* {{cite rowlett|index}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Italy|Engineering|Architecture|Lists}}\n{{Lighthouses}}\n{{Lighthouses in Europe}}\n{{Lighthouses of Italy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lighthouses in Italy}}\n[[Category:Lighthouses in Italy| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy]]\n[[Category:Water transport in Italy]]\n[[Category:Lists of lighthouses|Italy]]\n[[Category:Italy transport-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Rennboot", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApulia", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_lighthouses_in_Italy"}
{"title_page": "Tsarevich Ivan Ivanovich of Russia", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name        = Ivan Ivanovich\n| title       = Tsarevich of Russia (1554-1581)\n| image       = Iv\u00e1n el Terrible y su hijo, por Ili\u00e1 Repin.jpg\n| caption     = The wounded Ivan being cradled by his father in ''[[Ivan the Terrible and His Son Ivan on November 16, 1581|Ivan the Terrible killing his son]]'' by [[Ilya Repin]] ([[Tretyakov Gallery]], [[Moscow]])\n| spouse      = [[Eudoxia Saburova]]<br/>[[Praskovia Solova]]<br/>[[Yelena Sheremeteva]]\n| issue       =\n| house       = [[Rurik Dynasty|Rurik]]\n| house-type  = Dynasty\n| father      = [[Ivan IV of Russia|Ivan IV]]\n| mother      = [[Anastasia Romanovna]]\n| birth_date  = 28 March 1554\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1581|11|19|1554|3|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Alexandrov (town)|Alexandrov]]\n| burial_date =\n| burial_place= [[Cathedral of the Archangel]],<br> [[Moscow]]\n| religion    = [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]]\n}}\n\n'''Ivan Ivanovich''' (\u0418\u0432\u0430\u0301\u043d \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447) (28 March 1554 &ndash; 19 November 1581) of the House of [[Rurik]], was a [[Tsesarevich|Tsarevich]] ([[heir apparent]]) of [[Tsardom of Russia|Russia]]. He was the son of [[Ivan the Terrible]], who eventually killed him.\n\n==Early life==\nIvan was the second son of Ivan the Terrible by his first wife [[Anastasia Romanovna]]. His brother was [[Feodor I of Russia|Feodor]]. The young Ivan accompanied his father during the [[Massacre of Novgorod]] at the age of 15. For five weeks, he and his father would watch the [[Oprichnik]]s with enthusiasm and retire to church for prayer. At age 27, Ivan was at least as well read as his father, and in his free time, wrote a biography on [[Antony of Siya]]. Ivan is reputed to have once saved his father from an assassination attempt. A Livonian prisoner named Bykovski raised a sword against the Tsar, only to be rapidly stabbed by the Tsarevich.\n\n==Marriages==\nIn 1566, it was suggested that the 12-year-old Ivan marry [[Virginia Eriksdotter]], daughter of King [[Eric XIV of Sweden]], but this did not come about. At the age of seventeen, Ivan was betrothed to [[Eudoxia Saburova]], who had previously been proposed as a bride for Tsar Ivan. Indeed, she had been one of twelve women paraded before the Tsar in a [[bride-show]] for him to make a choice. The Tsar had rejected Eudoxia as a bride for himself but she was later married to the Tsar's son. The Tsar wanted his daughter-in-law to produce an heir very quickly, and this did not happen, so the Tsar banished her to a convent and got his son another bride. This second wife was [[Praskovia Solova]], who quickly met with the same fate as her predecessor, and was also put away into a convent. The Tsar then got his son a third wife, [[Yelena Sheremeteva]], who was found to be pregnant in October 1581. That child was presumably miscarried around the time when Ivan died by his father's hand in November 1581.\n\n[[Image:Wjatscheslaw Grigorjewitsch Schwarz 001.jpg|thumb|right|''Ivan the Terrible meditating at the deathbed of his son'' by [[Vyacheslav Schwarz]] (1861)]]\n[[File:Drevnosti RG v3 ill009 - Helmet of Ioan Ioanovich.jpg|thumb|right|{{Interlanguage link multi|Shlem|ru|3=\u0428\u0435\u043b\u043e\u043c}} (helmet) of Ivan Ivanovich, before 1557]]\n\n==Death==\nIvan Ivanovich is [[believed]] to have been killed by his [[father]], [[Ivan the Terrible]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perrie|first1=Maureen|last2=Pavlov|first2=Andrei|title=Ivan the Terrible|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mooABAAAQBAJ&pg=PA192|year=2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-89468-1|page=192}}</ref>\n\nIvan Ivanovich's relationship with his father began to deteriorate during the later stages of the [[Livonian War]]. Angry with his father for his military failures, Ivan demanded to be given command of some troops to liberate [[Siege of Pskov|besieged Pskov]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nTheir relationship further deteriorated when on 15 November 1581, the Tsar, after seeing his pregnant daughter-in-law wearing unconventionally light clothing, physically assaulted her. Hearing her screams, the Tsarevich rushed to his wife's defense, angrily shouting, \"You sent my first wife to a convent for no reason, you did the same with my second, and now you strike the third, causing the death of the son she holds in her womb.\" Yelena subsequently suffered a [[miscarriage]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}. The Tsarevich confronted his father on the matter, only to have the topic changed to his insubordination regarding Pskov. The elder Ivan accused his son of inciting rebellion, which the younger Ivan denied, but vehemently stuck to the view that Pskov should be liberated. Angered, Ivan's father struck him on the head with his [[sceptre]]. [[Boris Godunov]], who was present at the scene, tried to intervene but received blows himself. The younger Ivan fell, barely conscious and with a bleeding wound on his temple. The elder Ivan immediately threw himself at his son, kissing his face and trying to stop the bleeding, whilst repeatedly crying, \"May I be damned! I've killed my son! I've killed my son!\" The younger Ivan briefly regained consciousness and was reputed to have said \"I die as a devoted son and most humble servant\". For the next few days, the elder Ivan prayed incessantly for a miracle, but to no avail, and the Tsarevich died on 19 November 1581.\n\nIvan's death had grave consequences for Russia, since it left no competent heir to the throne. After the Tsar's death in 1584, his unprepared son [[Feodor I]] succeeded him with Godunov as ''de facto'' ruler. After Feodor's death, Russia entered a period of political uncertainty known as the [[Time of Troubles]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Troyat, Henri ''Ivan le Terrible''. Flammarion, Paris, 1982\n* de Madariaga, Isabel ''Ivan the Terrible''. Giulio Einaudi editore, 2005\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-roy|ru}}\n{{Succession box |\n  before=Dmitri Ivanovich|\n  title=[[List of heirs to the Russian throne|Heir to the Russian Throne]] |\n  years=1554&ndash;1581|\n  after=[[Feodor I]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Tsarevich of Russia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ivan Ivanovich Of Russia}}\n[[Category:Russian tsarevich]]\n[[Category:Heirs apparent who never acceded]]\n[[Category:Murdered Russian royalty]]\n[[Category:1554 births]]\n[[Category:1581 deaths]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Russia]]\n[[Category:16th-century Russian people]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name        = Ivan Ivanovich\n| title       = Tsarevich of Russia (1554-1581)\n| image       = Iv\u00e1n el Terrible y su hijo, por Ili\u00e1 Repin.jpg\n| caption     = The wounded Ivan being cradled by his father in ''[[Ivan the Terrible and His Son Ivan on November 16, 1581|Ivan the Terrible killing his son]]'' by [[Ilya Repin]] ([[Tretyakov Gallery]], [[Moscow]])\n| spouse      = [[Eudoxia Saburova]]<br/>[[Praskovia Solova]]<br/>[[Yelena Sheremeteva]]\n| issue       =\n| house       = [[Rurik Dynasty|Rurik]]\n| house-type  = Dynasty\n| father      = [[Ivan IV of Russia|Ivan IV]]\n| mother      = [[Anastasia Romanovna]]\n| birth_date  = 28 March 1554\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1581|11|19|1554|3|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Alexandrov (town)|Alexandrov]]\n| burial_date =\n| burial_place= [[Cathedral of the Archangel]],<br> [[Moscow]]\n| religion    = [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]]\n}}\n\n'''Ivan Ivanovich''' (\u0418\u0432\u0430\u0301\u043d \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447) (28 March 1554 &ndash; 19 November 1581) of the House of [[Rurik]], was a [[Tsesarevich|Tsarevich]] ([[heir apparent]]) of [[Tsardom of Russia|Russia]]. He was the son of [[Ivan the Terrible]], who eventually killed him.\n\n==Early life==\nIvan was the second son of Ivan the Terrible by his first wife [[Anastasia Romanovna]]. His brother was [[Feodor I of Russia|Feodor]]. The young Ivan accompanied his father during the [[Massacre of Novgorod]] at the age of 15. For five weeks, he and his father would watch the [[Oprichnik]]s with enthusiasm and retire to church for prayer. At age 27, Ivan was at least as well read as his father, and in his free time, wrote a biography on [[Antony of Siya]]. Ivan is reputed to have once saved his father from an assassination attempt. A Livonian prisoner named Bykovski raised a sword against the Tsar, only to be rapidly stabbed by the Tsarevich.\n\n==Marriages==\nIn 1566, it was suggested that the 12-year-old Ivan marry [[Virginia Eriksdotter]], daughter of King [[Eric XIV of Sweden]], but this did not come about. At the age of seventeen, Ivan was betrothed to [[Eudoxia Saburova]], who had previously been proposed as a bride for Tsar Ivan. Indeed, she had been one of twelve women paraded before the Tsar in a [[bride-show]] for him to make a choice. The Tsar had rejected Eudoxia as a bride for himself but she was later married to the Tsar's son. The Tsar wanted his daughter-in-law to produce an heir very quickly, and this did not happen, so the Tsar banished her to a convent and got his son another bride. This second wife was [[Praskovia Solova]], who quickly met with the same fate as her predecessor, and was also put away into a convent. The Tsar then got his son a third wife, [[Yelena Sheremeteva]], who was found to be pregnant in October 1581. That child was presumably miscarried around the time when Ivan died by his father's hand in November 1581.\n\n[[Image:Wjatscheslaw Grigorjewitsch Schwarz 001.jpg|thumb|right|''Ivan the Terrible meditating at the deathbed of his son'' by [[Vyacheslav Schwarz]] (1861)]]\n[[File:Drevnosti RG v3 ill009 - Helmet of Ioan Ioanovich.jpg|thumb|right|{{Interlanguage link multi|Shlem|ru|3=\u0428\u0435\u043b\u043e\u043c}} (helmet) of Ivan Ivanovich, before 1557]]\n\n==Death==\n[[Ivan Ivanovich]] is [[believed]] to have been [[killed]] by his [[father]], [[Ivan the Terrible]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perrie|first1=Maureen|last2=Pavlov|first2=Andrei|title=Ivan the Terrible|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mooABAAAQBAJ&pg=PA192|year=2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-89468-1|page=192}}</ref>\n\nIvan Ivanovich's relationship with his father began to deteriorate during the later stages of the [[Livonian War]]. Angry with his father for his military failures, Ivan demanded to be given command of some troops to liberate [[Siege of Pskov|besieged Pskov]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nTheir relationship further deteriorated when on 15 November 1581, the Tsar, after seeing his pregnant daughter-in-law wearing unconventionally light clothing, physically assaulted her. Hearing her screams, the Tsarevich rushed to his wife's defense, angrily shouting, \"You sent my first wife to a convent for no reason, you did the same with my second, and now you strike the third, causing the death of the son she holds in her womb.\" Yelena subsequently suffered a [[miscarriage]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}. The Tsarevich confronted his father on the matter, only to have the topic changed to his insubordination regarding Pskov. The elder Ivan accused his son of inciting rebellion, which the younger Ivan denied, but vehemently stuck to the view that Pskov should be liberated. Angered, Ivan's father struck him on the head with his [[sceptre]]. [[Boris Godunov]], who was present at the scene, tried to intervene but received blows himself. The younger Ivan fell, barely conscious and with a bleeding wound on his temple. The elder Ivan immediately threw himself at his son, kissing his face and trying to stop the bleeding, whilst repeatedly crying, \"May I be damned! I've killed my son! I've killed my son!\" The younger Ivan briefly regained consciousness and was reputed to have said \"I die as a devoted son and most humble servant\". For the next few days, the elder Ivan prayed incessantly for a miracle, but to no avail, and the Tsarevich died on 19 November 1581.\n\nIvan's death had grave consequences for Russia, since it left no competent heir to the throne. After the Tsar's death in 1584, his unprepared son [[Feodor I]] succeeded him with Godunov as ''de facto'' ruler. After Feodor's death, Russia entered a period of political uncertainty known as the [[Time of Troubles]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Troyat, Henri ''Ivan le Terrible''. Flammarion, Paris, 1982\n* de Madariaga, Isabel ''Ivan the Terrible''. Giulio Einaudi editore, 2005\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-roy|ru}}\n{{Succession box |\n  before=Dmitri Ivanovich|\n  title=[[List of heirs to the Russian throne|Heir to the Russian Throne]] |\n  years=1554&ndash;1581|\n  after=[[Feodor I]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Tsarevich of Russia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ivan Ivanovich Of Russia}}\n[[Category:Russian tsarevich]]\n[[Category:Heirs apparent who never acceded]]\n[[Category:Murdered Russian royalty]]\n[[Category:1554 births]]\n[[Category:1581 deaths]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Russia]]\n[[Category:16th-century Russian people]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unlinked:Ivan Ivanovich,Killed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsarevich_Ivan_Ivanovich_of_Russia"}
{"title_page": "Media censorship and disinformation during the Gezi Park protests", "text_new": "The 2013 [[Gezi Park protests]] in [[Turkey]] saw massive amounts of censorship and [[disinformation]] by the mainstream media,<ref name=\"GuardianPenguin\" /> especially by those supporting Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] and his [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP).<ref>{{cite news|author=Orhan Kemal Cengiz |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/07/turkish-press-censored.html |title=Shameful Examples Emerge Of Press Censorship in Turkey |publisher=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> A poll done by [[Istanbul Bilgi University]] in the first week of the protests showed that 84% of the demonstrators cited the lack of media coverage as a reason to join the protests, higher than the 56% of protesters who referred to the destruction of Gezi Park.<ref>{{cite news|author=Pelin Turgut |url=http://world.time.com/2013/06/06/as-turkeys-protests-continue-attention-falls-on-failures-of-turkish-media/ |title=As Turkey's Protests Continue, Attention Falls on Failures of Turkish Media |publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=6 June 2013 |accessdate=2015-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship during protests==\n[[File:Ntv-Van Media for sales.png|thumbnail|This [[NTV (Turkey)|NTV]] broadcast van has been covered with protest graffiti, in response to the indifference of mainstream media to protests.]]\n\n===History===\n{{Further|Censorship in Turkey}}\n[[Censorship]] is a common issue in Turkey. Since 2011, the AKP has increasingly levied restrictions on freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and internet use,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/05/world/europe/turkeys-glow-dims-as-government-limits-free-speech.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first1=Dan | last1=Bilefsky | first2=Sebnem | last2=Arsu | title=Turkey's Glow Dims as Government Limits Free Speech | date=4 January 2012}}</ref> and television content,<ref>{{cite news|author=Sibel Utku Bila |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/01/turkey-censorship-steinbeck.html |title=In Erdogan's Turkey, Censorship Finds Fertile Ground |publisher=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=2013-01-13 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> as well as the right to free assembly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/turkish-prime-minister-erdogan-sets-deadline-for-eu-admission-a-864579.html |title=Turkish Prime Minister Erdogan Sets Deadline for EU Admission |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |publisher=Spiegel.de |date=2012-10-31 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> It has also developed links with media groups, and used administrative and legal measures (including, in one case, a $2.5 billion tax fine) against critical media groups and critical journalists: \"over the last decade the AKP has built an informal, powerful, coalition of party-affiliated businessmen and media outlets whose livelihoods depend on the political order that Erdo\u011fan is constructing. Those who resist do so at their own risk.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-1039120 | title = Why Turkish Protesting | date = 22 September 2013 | location = [[Karachi]] | newspaper = [[CNN iReport]] | accessdate = 13 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Televisions===\n<blockquote>[On the afternoon of Friday, May 31, 2013]'' [[CNN T\u00fcrk|CNN Turk]] was broadcasting a food show, featuring the \"flavors of [[Ni\u011fde]].\" Other major Turkish news channels were showing a dance contest and a roundtable on study-abroad programs. It was a classic case of the [[The Revolution Will Not Be Televised|revolution not being televised]]. The whole country seemed to be experiencing a cognitive disconnect, with Twitter saying one thing, the government saying another, and the television off on another planet.</blockquote>\n\n[[File:Gezi park\u0131 2013-06-08 (51).jpg|thumb|Penguin art at Gezi Park, satirizing the extended CNN Turk broadcast of a documentary on penguins despite the massive protests occurring on the streets.<ref name=\"GuardianPenguin\">{{cite news | title = Why Turkey's mainstream media chose to show penguins rather than protests | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jun/09/turkey-mainstream-media-penguins-protests | date = 9 June 2013 | accessdate = 13 February 2014 | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | author = Kerem Oktem }}</ref>]]\n* At 1 am on 2 June, [[CNN T\u00fcrk|CNN Turk]] was broadcasting a documentary on penguins while [[CNN International]] was showing live coverage of the protests in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alfonso |first=Fernando |url=http://www.dailydot.com/news/cnn-turk-istanbul-riots-penguin-doc-social-media/ |title=CNN-Turk airs penguin documentary during Istanbul riots |publisher=The Daily Dot |date=2013-06-02 |accessdate=26 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Fleishman |first=Cooper |title=CNN-Turk airs penguin documentary during Istanbul riots |url=http://www.dailydot.com/news/cnn-turk-istanbul-riots-penguin-doc-social-media/ |publisher=dailydot.com |date=June 2, 2013 |accessdate=June 3, 2013}}</ref> \"Many of the protesters complained about the lack of coverage on Turkish television. Some newspapers too were largely silent on the protests: on Saturday morning [2 June], the lead article in ''[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]'', a major pro-government newspaper, was about Erdo\u011fan's campaign against smoking.\"<ref>[[New York Times]], 1 June 2013, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/02/world/europe/despite-protests-turkey-vows-to-push-ahead-with-plans-for-square.html?pagewanted=2&smid=tw-share Police Retreat as Protests Expand Through Turkey]</ref> Sabah's front page on 2 June did not feature the protests at all, but found space to cover \"President Abdullah Gul being presented with a horse during his official visit to Turkmenistan.\"<ref name=WSJ>Wall Street Journal, 3 June 2013, [https://blogs.wsj.com/middleeast/2013/06/03/amid-turkey-unrest-social-media-becomes-a-battleground/ Amid Turkey Unrest, Social Media Becomes a Battleground]</ref>\n* On 3 June, the TV [[game show]] Kelime Oyunu (''\"Word Game\"''), on [[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg HT]] TV, hosted by [[Ali \u0130hsan Varol]] supported the protests by placing 70 questions and answers (e.g. \"gazmaskesi\", gas masks) that referred to the protests. A previous attempt to smuggle protest support into other television shows included [[Kenan Do\u011fulu]] taking off his top on a Turkish TV show (\"Elidor Miss Turkey\", [[Star TV (Turkey)|Star TV]], 31 May) to reveal an \"Occupy Gezi\" T-shirt.\n[[File:Ntv-workers-chapulling.jpg|thumb|Protesters in front of [[NTV (Turkey)|NTV]], which also broadcast a documentary instead of the protests.]]\n\n* On 3 June, thousands of white collar people working in the financial district of Maslak and Levent were gathered in front of Do\u011fu\u015f Media Center to protest coverage by [[Do\u011fu\u015f Holding]]'s [[NTV (Turkey)|NTV]], one of the major news channels. NTV was forced to broadcast events live, while protesters chanted \"sat\u0131lm\u0131\u015f medya istemiyoruz\" (\"We do not want media that is for sale.\"), \"Tayyip istifa\" (\"Resign Tayyip\"), \"Her yer Taksim, her yer direni\u015f\" (\"Taksim everywhere, resistance everywhere\").<ref>{{cite web |url=http://haber.sol.org.tr/medya/ntv-haber-burnunun-dibinde-haberi-74030 |language=Turkish |title='NTV haber burnunun dibinde' &#124; soL Haber Portal\u0131 |publisher=Haber.sol.org.tr |accessdate=26 June 2013|date=2013-06-03 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gazeteciler.com/gundem/eylemler-sonuc-verdi-ntv-insafa-geldi-66959h.html |language=Turkish |title=Eylemler sonu\u00e7 verdi! NTV insafa geldi! |publisher=Gazeteciler.com |accessdate=26 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709005942/http://www.gazeteciler.com/gundem/eylemler-sonuc-verdi-ntv-insafa-geldi-66959h.html |archive-date=9 July 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Some NTV staff resigned in protest at the lack of coverage. The CEO of [[Do\u011fu\u015f Media Group]], Cem Ayd\u0131n, conceded that the criticisms were \"fair to a large extent\", and that \"Our audience feels like they were betrayed.\"<ref>BBC, 5 June 2013, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-22776946 Turkey protests resume in Istanbul after apology]</ref> Shortly after his comments, Ayd\u0131n left Do\u011fu\u015f Media.<ref>[[Hurriyet Daily News]], 13 June 2013, [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/dogus-media-ceo-takes-leave-amid-media-criticism-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=48753&NewsCatID=341 Do\u011fu\u015f Media CEO takes leave amid media criticism]</ref>\n\n===Newspapers===\n* Seven pro-government newspapers were published with an identical headline in support of Erdo\u011fan on June 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yesilgazete.org/blog/2013/06/07/al-birini-vur-otekine-6-musvedde-medya-gazetesinde-tek-baslik/ |title=Al birini Vur \u00f6tekine! 7 \"m\u00fcsvedde\" medya gazetesinde tek ba\u015fl\u0131k! \u2013 Ye\u015fil Gazete |publisher=Yesilgazete.org |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n\n===Social media===\nAs a result of the lack of mainstream media coverage, [[social media]] played a key role in keeping people informed, with Twitter [[hashtag]]s #OccupyGezi and #DirenGeziParki (\"Resist, Gezi Park\") being adopted.<ref name=\"TW\">Turkish Weekly, 1 June 2013, [http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/151041/-occupy-taksim-grows-in-spite-of-crackdown.html \u2018Occupy Taksim\u2019 grows in spite of crackdown] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915032134/http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/151041/-occupy-taksim-grows-in-spite-of-crackdown.html |date=2013-09-15 }}</ref><ref name=\"AlJ-stream\">{{cite news|url=http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201305302148-0022796|title=Protesters #OccupyGezi to save Istanbul park|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=31 May 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601073350/http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201305302148-0022796|archivedate=1 June 2013|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"Radikal1135724\">{{Cite news| url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/fotogaleri/turkiye/unluler_gezi_parki_ile_ilgili_twitterda_neler_soyledi-1135724-5|title=\u00dcnl\u00fcler Gezi Park\u0131 ile ilgili Twitter'da neler s\u00f6yledi?|newspaper=[[Radikal]]|date=31 May 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref> In the 12 hours from 4&nbsp;pm 31 May, there were more than 2 million tweets for the 3 leading hashtags, with 88% in Turkish and 90% of geolocated tweets coming from Turkey.<ref name=\"Barbera\" /> Erdo\u011fan said in a speech that \"There is now a menace which is called Twitter. The best examples of lies can be found there. To me, social media is the worst menace to society.\"<ref name=\"Letsch2June\">{{cite news |last=Costanze|first=Letsch|title=Turkish protests: Prime Minister blames opposition|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/02/turkish-protesters-control-istanbul-square|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=2 June 2013|location=London|date=2 June 2013}}</ref> A December 2012 [[Pew Research Center]] study showed 35% of Turks using social networking sites.<ref name=\"WSJ\" /><ref>[[Pew Research Center]], 12 December 2012, [http://www.pewglobal.org/2012/12/12/social-networking-popular-across-globe/ Social Networking Popular Across Globe]</ref>\n\nSixteen people in [[\u0130zmir]] and thirteen people in [[Adana]] were detained for posting provocative messages on Twitter<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/turkiye/izmirde_halki_isyana_tesvik_baskinlari_16_gozalti-1136298|title=\u0130zmir'de 'halk\u0131 isyana te\u015fvik' bask\u0131nlar\u0131: 16 g\u00f6zalt\u0131|date = 4 June 2013|newspaper=Radikal}}</ref> but were released later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Twitter g\u00f6zalt\u0131lar\u0131 serbest b\u0131rak\u0131ld\u0131|url=http://www.cnnturk.com/2013/turkiye/06/10/twitter.gozaltilari.serbest.birakildi/711174.0/|date=11 June 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>  ''[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]'' wrote that some of those people were arrested for tweets about actions like \"We've burned Bank Asia\", \"We destroyed the K\u00f6rfez training center\", \"We've burned the FEM training center\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Twitter tutuklamalar\u0131n\u0131n sebebi belli oldu|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/Gundem/2013/06/06/medyada-vandalizmi-aklama-operasyonu|newspaper=Sabah|date=6 June 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThere were reports that the 3G signal in some areas had been turned off; in response, some shops and offices removed security from their Wifi networks.<ref name=\"Barbera\">Pablo Barbera and Megan Metzger, Al Jazeera, 1 June, [http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2013/06/201361212350593971.html A breakout role for Twitter in the Taksim Square protests? ]</ref><ref>Kumi Naidoo, Al Jazeera, 1 June 2013, [http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2013/06/201361204546650196.html The last tree or the final straw? ]</ref> Rumours of censorship led to increasing use of [[virtual private network]]s (VPNs) during the protests.<ref>[[The Guardian]], 4 June 2013, [https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/jun/04/turkish-protestors-encryption-software-evade-censors Turkish protesters using encryption software to evade censors]</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Economist]]'', \"Mr Erdogan's perceived enemies\" have been \"inundated with menacing tweets.\" These include a correspondent covering the protests being called a \"dirty Armenian\" and \"a slut\" by pro-government supporters.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21579873-vicious-police-tactics-have-reclaimed-taksim-square-and-other-places-protest-high|title=Erdogan cracks down|journal=The Economist|accessdate=2 October 2015|date=2013-06-22}}</ref>\n\n===Reactions to censorship===\n* [[NTV (Turkey)|NTV Turkey]] refused to air a BBC World News package on press freedom in Turkey; in response, the BBC suspended its contract with the channel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement regarding BBC and NTV, Turkey|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/statements/bbc-ntv.html|publisher=bbc.co.uk|date=14 June 2013|accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>\n* A campaign was started to force [[CNN]] International to pull its name franchise from [[CNN T\u00fcrk]] in response to its lack of coverage of the protests as well as the aforementioned infamous penguin incident. More than 108,000 people signed the petition.<ref>{{cite news|author=Zeynep Erekli |title=CNN International must pull its name franchise from CNN Turk @TeamCNN |publisher=Change.org |date=2013-06-10}}</ref>\n\n===Pressure on journalists===\n\n* According to the Turkish Journalists Union (TGS), at least 22 journalists have been fired and 37 forced to quit over their coverage of the Gezi Park protests.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/turkish-journalists-fired-over-coverage-of-gezi-park-protests-8727133.html |title=Turkish journalists fired over coverage of Gezi Park protests |newspaper=The Independent |date=2013-07-23 |accessdate=2014-02-18 |location=London}}</ref>\n* The controversial mayor of Ankara, [[Melih G\u00f6k\u00e7ek]], who is also a member of the ruling AKP launched a [[Twitter]] campaign against Selin Girit of [[BBC]], accusing her of being an [[England|English]] agent and trying to undermine the Turkish economy in her reporting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.avrupatimes.com/politics/4769-bbc-turkish-reporter-selin-girit-intimidated-by-turkey.html |title=BBC Turkish reporter Selin Girit intimidated by Turkey |newspaper=Avrupa Times |date=2013-06-25 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n* Turkey's premier popular history magazine ''NTV Tarih'' got closed down by its administration, because it was preparing a special issue on Gezi Park protests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bianet.org/english/culture/148122-ntv-tarih-popular-history-magazine-closed |title=NTV Tarih, Popular History Magazine, Closed |publisher=Bianet |date=1 July 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> Owner of the magazine was Do\u011fu\u015f Media Group, also owner of the NTV television channel. CEO of the group [[Ferit \u015eahenk]] was cricitised for his auto-censorship policy, which was aimed not to anger the AKP government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/dogus-media-ceo-takes-leave-amid-media-criticism-.aspx?PageID=238&NID=48753&NewsCatID=341 |title=Do\u011fu\u015f Media CEO takes leave amid media criticism |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=13 June 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>  The Gezi Park issue later got published on the internet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yasarkenyazilantarih.com/ |title=Ya\u015farken Yaz\u0131lan Tarih |publisher=yasarkenyazilantarih.com |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> and as a book<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnnturk.com/2013/kultur.sanat/kitap/10/31/yasarken.yazilan.tarih/729245.0/ |title=Ya\u015farken Yaz\u0131lan Tarih |publisher=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |date=31 October 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>  by the sacked journalists of NTV Tarih.\n* Later in June, the state media regulator [[RT\u00dcK]] fined a number of channels (including [[Halk TV]] and [[Ulusal Kanal]]) \"for 'harming the physical, moral and mental development of children and young people' by broadcasting coverage of the Gezi Park protests\".<ref>[[Hurriyet Daily News]], 12 June 2013, [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/tv-watchdog-fines-live-streaming-of-gezi-protests-for-harming-development-of-children-youth-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=48655&NewsCatID=341 TV watchdog fines live streaming of Gezi protests for \u2018harming development of children, youth\u2019]</ref> Members of RT\u00dcK are appointed by the government, and the fines were approved by the 6 AKP members of the 9-member group, against the 3 votes of the opposition.<ref name=\"HDN48712\" /> [[Hayat TV (Turkey)|Hayat TV]], which had also given the protests extensive coverage, was ordered to stop broadcasting on 14 June, although RT\u00dcK reversed its decision in the face of protests.<ref>''[[Radikal]]'', 14 June 2013, [http://www.radikal.com.tr/turkiye/rtuk_hayat_tv_hakkindaki_kapatma_kararini_geri_cekti-1137640 RT\u00dcK, Hayat TV hakk\u0131ndaki kapatma karar\u0131n\u0131 geri \u00e7ekti]</ref>\n* The governor of [[Eski\u015fehir]] sent a threatening e-mail to the journalist [[\u0130smail Saymaz]], over his reports on a Gezi protester's murder in Eski\u015fehir.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/eskisehir-governor-threatens-journalist-over-reports-on-gezi-protesters-murder-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=55547&NewsCatID=341 |title=Eski\u015fehir governor threatens journalist over reports on Gezi protester's murder |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=2011-09-13 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n* Mehmet Barlas, chief editor of the pro-AKP newspaper [[Sabah]] wrote that the CEO of the [[Do\u011fan Holding]] [[Ayd\u0131n Do\u011fan]] should warn his writers who sympathize with Gezi park protesters. A few days later Akif Beki, a pro-AKP columnist started writing for [[H\u00fcrriyet]], Do\u011fan Holding's main newspaper.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/Yazarlar/barlas/2013/09/20/aydin-dogan-yazarlarini-yine-uyarmalidir |title=Ayd\u0131n Do\u011fan yazarlar\u0131n\u0131 yine uyarmal\u0131d\u0131r |author=Mehmet Barlas |newspaper=[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]] |date=20 September 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n* Administration of Sabah newspaper fired its ombudsman Yavuz Baydar, because he criticised newspaper's disinformative approach during Gezi protests.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yavuz Baydar |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/07/baydar-sabah-obudsman-fired-censorship.html |title=Shooting the Arbiter in Turkey: How Sabah Fired Its Ombudsman |newspaper=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=25 July 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Disinformation during protests==\nThe 2013 protests in Turkey witnessed a large amount of disinformation being spread by pro-[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]], [[conservative]], and [[Islamist]] media, also dubbed as ''Yanda\u015f Medya'' (\"Slanted Media\"). Leading newspapers said to be spreading disinformation were ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'', ''[[Yeni Akit]]'', ''[[Daily Sabah]]'', ''[[Star (Turkish newspaper)|Star]]'', ''[[Takvim]]'', ''[[Bug\u00fcn]]'', ''[[Ak\u015fam]]'', ''[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]]'', ''[[T\u00fcrkiye (newspaper)|T\u00fcrkiye]]'', ''[[Milli Gazete]]'', ''[[G\u00fcne\u015f (newspaper)|G\u00fcne\u015f]]'', and ''Milat'', among others. Leading TV channels spreading disinformation were [[Kanal 7]], [[24 (Turkey)|24]], \u00dclke TV, [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation|TRT]], [[Samanyolu TV|Samanyolu]], [[ATV Turkey|ATV]], [[TGRT Haber|TGRT]], [[Sky Turk 360]], TV Net, [[TV8 (Turkey)|TV8]], Beyaz TV, [[Kanalt\u00fcrk]], and Kanal A. Leading internet portals said to be spreading disinformation were Haber 7, Habervaktim, En Son Haber, and Rotahaber.\n* '''June 1:''' Some pro-AKP journalists like Nihal Bengisu Karaca claimed that women in headscarves were being attacked by Gezi protesters. One claimed case in [[Istanbul]]'s [[Kabata\u015f, Istanbul|Kabata\u015f]] district became the center of attention and pro-AKP media claimed that there was security camera footage of the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://haber.stargazete.com/politika/basortulu-anneye-saldirinin-goruntu-kayitlari-mercek-altinda/haber-762399 |title=Ba\u015f\u00f6rt\u00fcl\u00fc anneye sald\u0131r\u0131n\u0131n g\u00f6r\u00fcnt\u00fc kay\u0131tlar\u0131 mercek alt\u0131nda haberi |publisher=[[Star (Turkish newspaper)|Star]] |date=2013-06-14 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> However, the governor of Istanbul said that he didn't see any videos of an attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/istanbul-governor-says-he-didnt-see-any-video-of-attack-on-woman-by-gezi-protesters.aspx?pageID=238&nID=50564&NewsCatID=341 |title=Istanbul Governor says he didn't see any video of attack on woman by Gezi protesters |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=12 July 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> Eight months later, on 14 February 2014, the video was released, showing that there had been no attack on the woman, disproving her and the AKP's claims.<ref name=\"headscarf2014-1\" /><ref name=\"headscarf2014-2\" />\n* '''June 4:''' Pro-AKP newspapers like ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' claimed that protesters who took refuge in [[Dolmabah\u00e7e Mosque]] during a police raid had drunk beer inside the mosque.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/sigindiklari-camide-icki-ictiler-04.06.2013-529113 |title=S\u0131\u011f\u0131nd\u0131klar\u0131 camide i\u00e7ki i\u00e7tiler! |newspaper=[[Yeni \u015eafak]] |date=3 June 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> PM [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] said that they would release security cam videos of this action. However, the [[imam]] of Dolmabah\u00e7e mosque denied those allegations and no videos were ever released to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/pm-erdogan-repeats-previously-denied-reports-of-protesters-entering-mosque-with-shoes-on-.aspx?pageID=238&nid=48520 |title=PM Erdo\u011fan repeats previously denied reports of protesters entering mosque with shoes on |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=9 June 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> Later, the imam of the mosque got assigned to the mosque of a small village on the outskirts of Istanbul.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yasemin \u00c7ongar |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/09/gezi-mosque-alcohol-lie-muezzin-exile.html |title=Turkish Muezzin Who Couldn't Lie Is Exiled |newspaper=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=2013-09-23 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' claimed on the same day that Gezi protesters were preparing for a big provocation and planning to burn the streets an on the holy [[Islam]]ic day of [[Isra and Mi'raj]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/mirac-gecesinde-sokaklari-karistirma-plani-04.06.2013-529279 |title=Mirac gecesinde sokaklar\u0131 kar\u0131\u015ft\u0131rma plan\u0131 |newspaper=[[Yeni \u015eafak]] |date=3 June 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> ''Yeni \u015eafak'' also claimed that protests were organized by some Turkish advertising agencies and they released an open list of the agencies they accused of organizing the protests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/ajanslar-eyleme-sponsor-04.06.2013-529278?ref=manset-13|title=Ajanslar eyleme sponsor|author=Piri Medya|date=3 June 2013|work=Yeni \u015eafak|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 5:''' Mustafa Durdu, a columnist of the [[Islamic extremism|Islamist extremist]] ''Akit'' newspaper, claimed that protesters may even have performed [[group sex]] inside [[Dolmabah\u00e7e Mosque]].<ref>[http://www.habervaktim.com/yazar/59624/bunlar-cianin-cocuklari.html BUNLAR CIA\u2019n\u0131n \u00c7OCUKLARI - Mustafa Durdu<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225145410/http://www.habervaktim.com/yazar/59624/bunlar-cianin-cocuklari.html |date=December 25, 2014 }}</ref> \nTurkish public broadcasting service TRT aired footage of people burning the Turkish flag. The footage was originally aired in 2010 but featured doctored dates, implying the current demonstrations were somehow secessionist in nature.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ulusalkanal.com.tr/gundem/trtnin-bayrak-yaktilar-videosu-yalan-cikti-h11763.html|title=TRT'nin bayrak yakt\u0131lar videosu yalan \u00e7\u0131kt\u0131!|date = 5 June 2013|newspaper=Ulusalkanal}}</ref>\n* '''June 6:''' Pro-AKP newspapers like ''[[Sabah]]'' reported that the protests were planned by the Serbian civil society organization [[Otpor!]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/Gundem/2013/06/06/gezi-parki-olaylarinin-perde-arkasi|title=Gezi Park\u0131 olaylar\u0131n\u0131n perde arkas\u0131|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/09/gezi-protests-turkey-democratization.html|title=Is Turkey, After Gezi Protests, On Path to Democratization? - Al-Monitor: the Pulse of the Middle East|work=Al-Monitor|accessdate=2 October 2015|date=2013-09-19}}</ref> Pro-AKP newspaper ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' claimed that the Zello mobile app, which was used by protesters to communicate during the protests, was served to them by a source in [[Houston]] and that protesters were taking orders from that source.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/houstondan-olum-emri-06.06.2013-529835?ref=manset-2|title=Houston'dan \u00f6l\u00fcm emri|author=Piri Medya|date=5 June 2013|work=Yeni \u015eafak|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>  \n* '''June 7:''' Police officer Mustafa Sar\u0131 died after falling off a bridge into an underpass while pursuing protesters in [[Adana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/news/turkish-police-officer-bridge-309/|title=Turkish policeman dead after falling from bridge while pursuing protesters|work=RT English|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> However, pro-government media sources like Rotahaber claimed that protesters pushed the police officer from the bridge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://haber.rotahaber.com/gostericilerin-kopruden-attigi-komiser-oldu_374167.html|title=G\u00f6stericilerin k\u00f6pr\u00fcden att\u0131\u011f\u0131 komiser \u00f6ld\u00fc - G\u00fcndem Haberleri - G\u00fcncel Haber - Haber - Spor Haberleri- S\u0131cak haber - Yerel Haber<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> Family of Mustafa Sar\u0131 denied those claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/turkiye/komiser_mustafa_sarinin_ailesi_atilmadi_dustu_iddialar_spekulasyon-1137019|title=Komiser Mustafa Sar\u0131'n\u0131n ailesi: At\u0131lmad\u0131 d\u00fc\u015ft\u00fc, iddialar spek\u00fclasyon|date=6 October 2013|work=Radikal|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 10:''' The newspaper ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' claimed that a theatre play called \"Mi Minor\", allegedly supported by an agency in [[United Kingdom|Britain]], had held rehearsals of \"revolution\" in Turkey for months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-actor-threatened-over-his-gezi-park-support-.aspx?PageID=238&NID=48568&NewsCatID=341|title=Turkish actor threatened over his Gezi Park support - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 12:''' The state-owned [[Anadolu Agency]] provided extensive reporting of protests in London over the [[G8]], and attempted to create a Twitter campaign around the [[hashtag]] #occupylondon, which was picked up by AKP supporters.<ref name=\"HDN48712\">[[Hurriyet Daily News]], 12 June 2013, [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-politicians-slam-foreign-media-coverage-of-the-gezi-park-protests.aspx?pageID=238&nID=48712&NewsCatID=338 Turkish politicians slam foreign media coverage of the Gezi Park protests]</ref>\n* '''June 13:''' The [[Islamism|Islamist]] ''[[Yeni Akit|Akit]]'' newspaper claimed that [[prostitution]] and [[group sex]] was common at Gezi park after 2 am. They based this claim on an \"anonymous journalist who saw this happening with his own eyes and told it to someone else\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.habervaktim.com/haber/330092/kendi-gozlerimle-gordum.html|title=Kendi G\u00f6zlerimle G\u00f6rd\u00fcm|date=13 June 2013|work=Habervaktim|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 14:''' Pro-government [[internet portal]] RotaHaber claimed that a Turkish national working as security chief at the [[United States]] embassy in [[Adana]] was active during protests and that he was an American agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://haber.rotahaber.com/abd-ajani-gezi-parki-eyleminde_376418.html#ixzz2lJqmZZg3|title=ABD ajan\u0131 Gezi Park\u0131 eyleminde...! - G\u00fcndem Haberleri - G\u00fcncel Haber - Haber - Spor Haberleri- S\u0131cak haber - Yerel Haber<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n* '''June 15:''' ''[[Yeni Akit|Akit]]'' accused supermarket chain [[Migros]] of delivering free supplies to the protesters at Gezi park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.habervaktim.com/haber/330233/eylemcileri-migros-besliyor.html|title=Eylemcileri Migros Besliyor|date=14 June 2013|work=Habervaktim|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> However, goods delivered to the park were bought by protesters through supermarket's internet shop.\n* '''June 18:''' After the clearing of Gezi Park camp, [[Erdem G\u00fcnd\u00fcz]] started the Standing Man/Woman protest that spread to all over Turkey. Pro-AKP newspapers claimed that standing protest is a [[CIA]] tactic from their handbook for non-violent action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://haber.stargazete.com/guncel/duran-adam-eylemi-cia-taktigi-cikti/haber-763641|title=Duran Adam Eylemi CIA Takti\u011fi \u00c7\u0131kt\u0131!|work=Star.com.tr|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> \n[[Takvim]] newspaper devoted its front page to a fake \"interview\" with [[CNN]]'s [[Christiane Amanpour]], in which Amanpour supposedly confesses that CNN's coverage of the protests was motivated by \"the express interest of destabilizing Turkey for international business interests\". The paper included a small disclaimer on the 14th page, saying \"This interview is not real, but what you will read here is real.\"<ref>{{ cite news | url = http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-daily-defames-cnn-anchor-christiane-amanpour.aspx?pageID=238&nID=49022&NewsCatID=341 | title = 'Shame on you,' Amanpour reacts to Turkish daily that published fake interview | date = 18 June 2013 | accessdate = 14 February 2014 | newspaper = [[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] }}</ref> Takvim newspaper also sued Amanpour.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/18/christiane-amanpour-takvim-turkish-newspaper_n_3460023.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Katherine | last=Fung | title=Christiane Amanpour Slams Turkish Newspaper For Fake Interview | date=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n* '''June 18:''' Pro-AKP [[internet portal]] Haber 7 claimed that during the first days of the protests, anti-government protesters were planning a civilian [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] by occupying PM [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]'s [[Ankara]] home and [[Istanbul]] office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haber7.com/guncel/haber/1041088-basbakan-erdoganin-evine-3-bin-kisiyle-baskin|title=Ba\u015fbakan Erdo\u011fan'\u0131n evine 3 bin ki\u015fiyle bask\u0131n|date=21 June 2013|work=Haber7|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 24:''' During one of the public forums in [[Istanbul]], which was televised live on Halk TV, a protester said that maybe they should wear police uniforms to protest police brutality. Pro-AKP media sources like ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' served this as \"Halk TV is planning a provocation by telling protesters to wear police uniforms and make false flag attacks\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/polis-degilsen-kiyafet-alamazsin-25.06.2013-535270|title=Polis de\u011filsen k\u0131yafet alamazs\u0131n|author=Piri Medya|date=24 June 2013|work=Yeni \u015eafak|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 27:''' Ethem Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck was shot dead by a police officer during the protests in [[Ankara]]. Pro-AKP newspapers released pictures of Ethem Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck holding an assault rifle and claimed that he was the member of a [[terrorist]] organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haber7.com/guncel/haber/1043150-sarisulukle-ilgili-cok-tartisilan-fotograf|title=Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck'le ilgili \u00e7ok tart\u0131\u015f\u0131lan foto\u011fraf!|date=27 June 2013|work=Haber7|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> However, later it was found out that those pictures were taken when Ethem Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck was working as a laborer for the construction of a military post.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.radikal.com.tr/turkiye/ethem_sarisulukun_fotografi_kampta_degil_karakolda_cekilmis-1139428 | title = Ethem Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck'\u00fcn foto\u011fraf\u0131 kampta de\u011fil karakolda \u00e7ekilmi\u015f | date = 27 June 2013 | accessdate = 14 February 2014 | newspaper = [[Radikal]] | last = Dursun | first = Ay\u015feg\u00fcl }}</ref>\n* '''July 22:''' Pro-AKP businessman Zeynel Abidin Erdem claimed that some source in [[Mexico]] bought 600 pizzas for the gezi park protesters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazete5.com/haber/gezi-parki-na-600-pizza-siparisi-hangi-ulkeden-odendi-347757|title=Gezi Park\u0131'na 600 pizza sipari\u015fi hangi \u00fclkeden \u00f6dendi?|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> \n* '''August 24:''' The Islamist ''[[Yeni Akit|Akit]]'' newspaper claimed that Gezi protesters were preparing for a big provocation on the August 30 Victory Day celebrations.<ref>[http://www.habervaktim.com/haber/340105/geziciler-30-agustosta-provokasyona-hazirlaniyor.html Geziciler 30 A\u011fustos\u2019ta Provokasyona Haz\u0131rlan\u0131yor<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225145414/http://www.habervaktim.com/haber/340105/geziciler-30-agustosta-provokasyona-hazirlaniyor.html |date=December 25, 2014 }}</ref>\n* '''August 26:''' World famous linguist and activist [[Noam Chomsky]] accused the pro-government ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' newspaper of fabricating some parts of an interview that was done with him via [[email]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/chomsky-accuses-turkish-daily-of-fabricating-parts-of-interview.aspx?pageID=238&nID=53554&NewsCatID=341|title=Chomsky accuses Turkish daily of fabricating parts of interview - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> The administration of ''Yeni \u015eafak'' denied this allegation and promised to release the original English content of emails. However, the released content was full of grammatical mistakes. Later it was found out that ''Yeni \u015eafak'' used the [[Google Translate]] service to translate fabricated Turkish content to English and served that as the original interview.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://blogs.wsj.com/emergingeurope/2013/09/05/turkish-newspapers-fake-chomsky-interview-lost-in-translation/ | work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> After grammatical errors, particularly \"milk port\" became a sensation at social media, ''Yeni \u015eafak'' finally admitted some parts were fabricated and removed the interview from its web site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-daily-admits-to-making-up-parts-of-chomsky-interview-releases-alleged-text-.aspx?PageID=238&NID=53617&NewsCatID=341|title=Turkish daily admits to making up parts of Chomsky interview, releases alleged text - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-daily-apologizes-for-fabricated-chomsky-interview.aspx?pageID=238&nID=53668&NewsCatID=341|title=Turkish daily apologizes for fabricated Chomsky interview - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''September 9:''' [[\u0130stanbul]] was a candidate for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]], but lost out to [[Tokyo]]. Pro-AKP media and government officials blamed Gezi protesters of conspiring internationally so that \u0130stanbul would lose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/world/europe/turkish-officials-blame-protesters-for-failed-olympics-bid|title=Turkish officials blame protesters for failed Olympics bid|author=Thomas Seibert|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> \n* '''September 28:''' Beyaz TV, which is owned by the son of the mayor of [[Ankara]], aired a program showing a 13-year-old child who claimed that he was paid by Gezi park protesters to throw stones at the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/tas-atmak-5-tl-tomanin-onune-yatmak-10-tl-27.09.2013-569124|title=Ta\u015f atmak 5 TOMA'n\u0131n \u00f6n\u00fcne yatmak 10 TL|author=Piri Medya|date=27 September 2013|work=Yeni \u015eafak|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> The child also said that \"protestors were probably drinking cat blood at the Gezi park\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yurtgazetesi.com.tr/gundem/gezide-kedi-kani-iciyorlardi-h42479.html|title=Gezi'de kedi kan\u0131 i\u00e7iyorlard\u0131|date=29 September 2013|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''October:''' During autumn, [[Istanbul]] witnessed long traffic jams. Pro-AKP journalists accused Gezi protesters of deliberately causing traffic jams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gundem.milliyet.com.tr/trafik-lobisinin-isi-mi-/gundem/detay/1776162/default.htm|title=Trafik lobisinin i\u015fi mi?|date=11 October 2013|work=MILLIYET HABER - T\u00dcRKIYE'NIN HABER SITESI|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> \n* '''November 3:''' The day after the grand opening of [[Marmaray]] project, many technical problems occurred.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/marmaray-calm-on-second-day-after-first-days-storm-of-technical-problems.aspx?pageID=238&nID=57176&NewsCatID=341|title=Marmaray calm on second day after first day's storm of technical problems - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> Pro-AKP T\u00fcrkiye newspaper accused Gezi protesters of delibaretly sabotaging Marmaray.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turkiyegazetesi.com.tr/gundem/97567.aspx|title=Marmaray'a gezi sabotaj\u0131|author=turkiyegazetesi editor|date=3 November 2013|work=turkiyegazetesi.com.tr|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''November 20:''' The pro-AKP ''[[Takvim]]'' newspaper, which printed a fabricated interview with [[CNN]]'s [[Christiane Amanpour]], claimed that seven Turkish Jewish citizens who did their military service in [[Israel]] were agents of [[Mossad]] and they were the leaders of Gezi protests. The newspaper also accused [[CNN]] and [[BBC]] of being part of \"this dirty plan\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takvim.com.tr/Guncel/2013/11/20/mossad-gezisi|title=Mossad Gezi'si|work=takvim.com.tr|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''February 14:''' Months after the end of the protests, video footage revealed that there had in fact been no attack on a woman wearing a [[headscarf]] by protesters on June 1. The woman and Prime Minister Erdo\u011fan had claimed in press conferences and political rallies that protesters had attacked her and her baby.<ref name=\"headscarf2014-1\">{{cite news | title = Released footage shows no physical attack on headscarf-wearing woman during Gezi protests | url = http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/163179/released-footage-shows-no-physical-attack-on-headscarf-wearing-woman-during-gezi-protests.html | date = 14 February 2014 | newspaper = Turkish Weekly }}</ref><ref name=\"headscarf2014-2\">{{cite news | title = Video casts doubt over alleged attack on headscarved woman | url = http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2014/Feb-14/247358-video-casts-doubt-over-alleged-attack-on-headscarved-woman.ashx | date = 14 February 2014 | newspaper = [[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]] }}</ref>\n* '''July 14:''' Pro-AKP ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' released an article titled \"The Horrible Istanbul Plan of Gezi Protestors\" on their internet portal. The article claimed that Gezi protesters are conspiring to undermine the AKP government by wasting water in order to empty the dams supplying \u0130stanbul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/national_pro-govt-media-gezi-protesters-conspiring-to-use-up-istanbuls-water_353227.html|title=Pro-gov't media: Gezi protesters conspiring to use up \u0130stanbul's water|date=16 July 2014|work=TodaysZaman|accessdate=2 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818200817/http://www.todayszaman.com/national_pro-govt-media-gezi-protesters-conspiring-to-use-up-istanbuls-water_353227.html|archivedate=18 August 2015|df=}}</ref> After the article became a source of mocking nationwide, Yeni \u015eafak removed the article from their web site.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Backward Run]]'' ([[Turkish language|Tr]]: ''Tornistan'') a Turkish animated short film about media censorship during the 2013 protests<ref>{{cite news  |  title = Tornistan: Turkey's summer of anti-government protests | first = Nabeelah | last = Shabbir | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/mar/11/tornistan-turkey-animated-film-gezi-park | date= 2014-03-11 | accessdate= 2014-07-07 | publisher = [[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Disinformation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Media censorship and disinformation during the 2013-14 protests in Turkey}}\n[[Category:Censorship in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Media freedom in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Gezi Park protests]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "text_old": "The 2013 [[Gezi Park protests]] in [[Turkey]] saw massive amounts of censorship and [[disinformation]] by the mainstream media,<ref name=\"GuardianPenguin\" /> especially by those supporting Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] and his [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP).<ref>{{cite news|author=Orhan Kemal Cengiz |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/07/turkish-press-censored.html |title=Shameful Examples Emerge Of Press Censorship in Turkey |publisher=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> A poll done by [[Istanbul Bilgi University]] in the first week of the protests showed that 84% of the demonstrators cited the lack of media coverage as a reason to join the protests, higher than the 56% of protesters who referred to the destruction of Gezi Park.<ref>{{cite news|author=Pelin Turgut |url=http://world.time.com/2013/06/06/as-turkeys-protests-continue-attention-falls-on-failures-of-turkish-media/ |title=As Turkey's Protests Continue, Attention Falls on Failures of Turkish Media |publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=6 June 2013 |accessdate=2015-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship during protests==\n[[File:Ntv-Van Media for sales.png|thumbnail|This [[NTV (Turkey)|NTV]] broadcast van has been covered with protest graffiti, in response to the indifference of mainstream media to protests.]]\n\n===History===\n{{Further|Censorship in Turkey}}\n[[Censorship]] is a common issue in Turkey. Since 2011, the AKP has increasingly levied restrictions on freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and internet use,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/05/world/europe/turkeys-glow-dims-as-government-limits-free-speech.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first1=Dan | last1=Bilefsky | first2=Sebnem | last2=Arsu | title=Turkey's Glow Dims as Government Limits Free Speech | date=4 January 2012}}</ref> and television content,<ref>{{cite news|author=Sibel Utku Bila |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/01/turkey-censorship-steinbeck.html |title=In Erdogan's Turkey, Censorship Finds Fertile Ground |publisher=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=2013-01-13 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> as well as the right to free assembly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/turkish-prime-minister-erdogan-sets-deadline-for-eu-admission-a-864579.html |title=Turkish Prime Minister Erdogan Sets Deadline for EU Admission |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |publisher=Spiegel.de |date=2012-10-31 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> It has also developed links with media groups, and used administrative and legal measures (including, in one case, a $2.5 billion tax fine) against critical media groups and critical journalists: \"over the last decade the AKP has built an informal, powerful, coalition of party-affiliated businessmen and media outlets whose livelihoods depend on the political order that Erdo\u011fan is constructing. Those who resist do so at their own risk.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-1039120 | title = Why Turkish Protesting | date = 22 September 2013 | location = [[Karachi]] | newspaper = [[CNN iReport]] | accessdate = 13 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Televisions===\n<blockquote>[On the afternoon of Friday, May 31, 2013]'' [[CNN T\u00fcrk|CNN Turk]] was broadcasting a food show, featuring the \"flavors of [[Ni\u011fde]].\" Other major Turkish news channels were showing a dance contest and a roundtable on study-abroad programs. It was a classic case of the [[The Revolution Will Not Be Televised|revolution not being televised]]. The whole country seemed to be experiencing a cognitive disconnect, with Twitter saying one thing, the government saying another, and the television off on another planet.</blockquote>\n\n[[File:Gezi park\u0131 2013-06-08 (51).jpg|thumb|Penguin art at Gezi Park, satirizing the extended CNN Turk broadcast of a documentary on penguins despite the massive protests occurring on the streets.<ref name=\"GuardianPenguin\">{{cite news | title = Why Turkey's mainstream media chose to show penguins rather than protests | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jun/09/turkey-mainstream-media-penguins-protests | date = 9 June 2013 | accessdate = 13 February 2014 | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | author = Kerem Oktem }}</ref>]]\n* At 1 am on 2 June, [[CNN T\u00fcrk|CNN Turk]] was broadcasting a documentary on penguins while [[CNN International]] was showing live coverage of the protests in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alfonso |first=Fernando |url=http://www.dailydot.com/news/cnn-turk-istanbul-riots-penguin-doc-social-media/ |title=CNN-Turk airs penguin documentary during Istanbul riots |publisher=The Daily Dot |date=2013-06-02 |accessdate=26 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Fleishman |first=Cooper |title=CNN-Turk airs penguin documentary during Istanbul riots |url=http://www.dailydot.com/news/cnn-turk-istanbul-riots-penguin-doc-social-media/ |publisher=dailydot.com |date=June 2, 2013 |accessdate=June 3, 2013}}</ref> \"Many of the protesters complained about the lack of coverage on Turkish television. Some newspapers too were largely silent on the protests: on Saturday morning [2 June], the lead article in ''[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]'', a major pro-government newspaper, was about Erdo\u011fan's campaign against smoking.\"<ref>[[New York Times]], 1 June 2013, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/02/world/europe/despite-protests-turkey-vows-to-push-ahead-with-plans-for-square.html?pagewanted=2&smid=tw-share Police Retreat as Protests Expand Through Turkey]</ref> Sabah's front page on 2 June did not feature the protests at all, but found space to cover \"President Abdullah Gul being presented with a horse during his official visit to Turkmenistan.\"<ref name=WSJ>Wall Street Journal, 3 June 2013, [https://blogs.wsj.com/middleeast/2013/06/03/amid-turkey-unrest-social-media-becomes-a-battleground/ Amid Turkey Unrest, Social Media Becomes a Battleground]</ref>\n* On 3 June, the TV [[game show]] Kelime Oyunu (''\"Word Game\"''), on [[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg HT]] TV, hosted by [[Ali \u0130hsan Varol]] supported the protests by placing 70 questions and answers (e.g. \"gazmaskesi\", gas masks) that referred to the protests. A previous attempt to smuggle protest support into other television shows included [[Kenan Do\u011fulu]] taking off his top on a Turkish TV show (\"Elidor Miss Turkey\", [[Star TV (Turkey)|Star TV]], 31 May) to reveal an \"Occupy Gezi\" T-shirt.\n[[File:Ntv-workers-chapulling.jpg|thumb|Protesters in front of [[NTV (Turkey)|NTV]], which also broadcast a documentary instead of the protests.]]\n\n* On 3 June, thousands of white collar people working in the financial district of Maslak and Levent were gathered in front of Do\u011fu\u015f Media Center to protest coverage by [[Do\u011fu\u015f Holding]]'s [[NTV (Turkey)|NTV]], one of the major news channels. NTV was forced to broadcast events live, while protesters chanted \"sat\u0131lm\u0131\u015f medya istemiyoruz\" (\"We do not want media that is for sale.\"), \"Tayyip istifa\" (\"Resign Tayyip\"), \"Her yer Taksim, her yer direni\u015f\" (\"Taksim everywhere, resistance everywhere\").<ref>{{cite web |url=http://haber.sol.org.tr/medya/ntv-haber-burnunun-dibinde-haberi-74030 |language=Turkish |title='NTV haber burnunun dibinde' &#124; soL Haber Portal\u0131 |publisher=Haber.sol.org.tr |accessdate=26 June 2013|date=2013-06-03 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gazeteciler.com/gundem/eylemler-sonuc-verdi-ntv-insafa-geldi-66959h.html |language=Turkish |title=Eylemler sonu\u00e7 verdi! NTV insafa geldi! |publisher=Gazeteciler.com |accessdate=26 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709005942/http://www.gazeteciler.com/gundem/eylemler-sonuc-verdi-ntv-insafa-geldi-66959h.html |archive-date=9 July 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Some NTV staff resigned in protest at the lack of coverage. The CEO of [[Do\u011fu\u015f Media Group]], Cem Ayd\u0131n, conceded that the criticisms were \"fair to a large extent\", and that \"Our audience feels like they were betrayed.\"<ref>BBC, 5 June 2013, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-22776946 Turkey protests resume in Istanbul after apology]</ref> Shortly after his comments, Ayd\u0131n left Do\u011fu\u015f Media.<ref>[[Hurriyet Daily News]], 13 June 2013, [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/dogus-media-ceo-takes-leave-amid-media-criticism-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=48753&NewsCatID=341 Do\u011fu\u015f Media CEO takes leave amid media criticism]</ref>\n\n===Newspapers===\n* Seven pro-government newspapers were published with an identical headline in support of Erdo\u011fan on June 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yesilgazete.org/blog/2013/06/07/al-birini-vur-otekine-6-musvedde-medya-gazetesinde-tek-baslik/ |title=Al birini Vur \u00f6tekine! 7 \"m\u00fcsvedde\" medya gazetesinde tek ba\u015fl\u0131k! \u2013 Ye\u015fil Gazete |publisher=Yesilgazete.org |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n\n===Social media===\nAs a result of the lack of mainstream media coverage, [[social media]] played a key role in keeping people informed, with Twitter [[hashtag]]s #OccupyGezi and #DirenGeziParki (\"Resist, Gezi Park\") being adopted.<ref name=\"TW\">Turkish Weekly, 1 June 2013, [http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/151041/-occupy-taksim-grows-in-spite-of-crackdown.html \u2018Occupy Taksim\u2019 grows in spite of crackdown] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915032134/http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/151041/-occupy-taksim-grows-in-spite-of-crackdown.html |date=2013-09-15 }}</ref><ref name=\"AlJ-stream\">{{cite news|url=http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201305302148-0022796|title=Protesters #OccupyGezi to save Istanbul park|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=31 May 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601073350/http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201305302148-0022796|archivedate=1 June 2013|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"Radikal1135724\">{{Cite news| url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/fotogaleri/turkiye/unluler_gezi_parki_ile_ilgili_twitterda_neler_soyledi-1135724-5|title=\u00dcnl\u00fcler Gezi Park\u0131 ile ilgili Twitter'da neler s\u00f6yledi?|newspaper=[[Radikal]]|date=31 May 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref> In the 12 hours from 4&nbsp;pm 31 May, there were more than 2 million tweets for the 3 leading hashtags, with 88% in Turkish and 90% of geolocated tweets coming from Turkey.<ref name=\"Barbera\" /> Erdo\u011fan said in a speech that \"There is now a menace which is called Twitter. The best examples of lies can be found there. To me, social media is the worst menace to society.\"<ref name=\"Letsch2June\">{{cite news |last=Costanze|first=Letsch|title=Turkish protests: Prime Minister blames opposition|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/02/turkish-protesters-control-istanbul-square|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=2 June 2013|location=London|date=2 June 2013}}</ref> A December 2012 [[Pew Research Center]] study showed 35% of Turks using social networking sites.<ref name=\"WSJ\" /><ref>[[Pew Research Center]], 12 December 2012, [http://www.pewglobal.org/2012/12/12/social-networking-popular-across-globe/ Social Networking Popular Across Globe]</ref>\n\nSixteen people in [[\u0130zmir]] and thirteen people in [[Adana]] were detained for posting provocative messages on Twitter<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/turkiye/izmirde_halki_isyana_tesvik_baskinlari_16_gozalti-1136298|title=\u0130zmir'de 'halk\u0131 isyana te\u015fvik' bask\u0131nlar\u0131: 16 g\u00f6zalt\u0131|date = 4 June 2013|newspaper=Radikal}}</ref> but were released later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Twitter g\u00f6zalt\u0131lar\u0131 serbest b\u0131rak\u0131ld\u0131|url=http://www.cnnturk.com/2013/turkiye/06/10/twitter.gozaltilari.serbest.birakildi/711174.0/|date=11 June 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>  ''[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]'' wrote that some of those people were arrested for tweets about actions like \"We've burned Bank Asia\", \"We destroyed the K\u00f6rfez training center\", \"We've burned the FEM training center\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Twitter tutuklamalar\u0131n\u0131n sebebi belli oldu|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/Gundem/2013/06/06/medyada-vandalizmi-aklama-operasyonu|newspaper=Sabah|date=6 June 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThere were reports that the 3G signal in some areas had been turned off; in response, some shops and offices removed security from their Wifi networks.<ref name=\"Barbera\">Pablo Barbera and Megan Metzger, Al Jazeera, 1 June, [http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2013/06/201361212350593971.html A breakout role for Twitter in the Taksim Square protests? ]</ref><ref>Kumi Naidoo, Al Jazeera, 1 June 2013, [http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2013/06/201361204546650196.html The last tree or the final straw? ]</ref> Rumours of censorship led to increasing use of [[virtual private network]]s (VPNs) during the protests.<ref>[[The Guardian]], 4 June 2013, [https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/jun/04/turkish-protestors-encryption-software-evade-censors Turkish protesters using encryption software to evade censors]</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Economist]]'', \"Mr Erdogan's perceived enemies\" have been \"inundated with menacing tweets.\" These include a correspondent covering the protests being called a \"dirty Armenian\" and \"a slut\" by pro-government supporters.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21579873-vicious-police-tactics-have-reclaimed-taksim-square-and-other-places-protest-high|title=Erdogan cracks down|journal=The Economist|accessdate=2 October 2015|date=2013-06-22}}</ref>\n\n===Reactions to censorship===\n* [[NTV (Turkey)|NTV Turkey]] refused to air a BBC World News package on press freedom in Turkey; in response, the BBC suspended its contract with the channel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement regarding BBC and NTV, Turkey|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/statements/bbc-ntv.html|publisher=bbc.co.uk|date=14 June 2013|accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>\n* A campaign was started to force [[CNN]] International to pull its name franchise from [[CNN T\u00fcrk]] in response to its lack of coverage of the protests as well as the aforementioned infamous penguin incident. More than 108,000 people signed the petition.<ref>{{cite news|author=Zeynep Erekli |title=CNN International must pull its name franchise from CNN Turk @TeamCNN |publisher=Change.org |date=2013-06-10}}</ref>\n\n===Pressure on journalists===\n\n* According to the Turkish Journalists Union (TGS), at least 22 journalists have been fired and 37 forced to quit over their coverage of the Gezi Park protests.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/turkish-journalists-fired-over-coverage-of-gezi-park-protests-8727133.html |title=Turkish journalists fired over coverage of Gezi Park protests |newspaper=The Independent |date=2013-07-23 |accessdate=2014-02-18 |location=London}}</ref>\n* The controversial mayor of Ankara, [[Melih G\u00f6k\u00e7ek]], who is also a member of the ruling AKP launched a [[Twitter]] campaign against Selin Girit of [[BBC]], accusing her of being an [[England|English]] agent and trying to undermine the Turkish economy in her reporting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.avrupatimes.com/politics/4769-bbc-turkish-reporter-selin-girit-intimidated-by-turkey.html |title=BBC Turkish reporter Selin Girit intimidated by Turkey |newspaper=Avrupa Times |date=2013-06-25 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n* Turkey's premier popular history magazine ''NTV Tarih'' got closed down by its administration, because it was preparing a special issue on Gezi Park protests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bianet.org/english/culture/148122-ntv-tarih-popular-history-magazine-closed |title=NTV Tarih, Popular History Magazine, Closed |publisher=Bianet |date=1 July 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> Owner of the magazine was Do\u011fu\u015f Media Group, also owner of the NTV television channel. CEO of the group [[Ferit \u015eahenk]] was cricitised for his auto-censorship policy, which was aimed not to anger the AKP government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/dogus-media-ceo-takes-leave-amid-media-criticism-.aspx?PageID=238&NID=48753&NewsCatID=341 |title=Do\u011fu\u015f Media CEO takes leave amid media criticism |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=13 June 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>  The Gezi Park issue later got published on the internet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yasarkenyazilantarih.com/ |title=Ya\u015farken Yaz\u0131lan Tarih |publisher=yasarkenyazilantarih.com |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> and as a book<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnnturk.com/2013/kultur.sanat/kitap/10/31/yasarken.yazilan.tarih/729245.0/ |title=Ya\u015farken Yaz\u0131lan Tarih |publisher=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |date=31 October 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>  by the sacked journalists of NTV Tarih.\n* Later in June, the state media regulator [[RT\u00dcK]] fined a number of channels (including [[Halk TV]] and [[Ulusal Kanal]]) \"for 'harming the physical, moral and mental development of children and young people' by broadcasting coverage of the Gezi Park protests\".<ref>[[Hurriyet Daily News]], 12 June 2013, [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/tv-watchdog-fines-live-streaming-of-gezi-protests-for-harming-development-of-children-youth-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=48655&NewsCatID=341 TV watchdog fines live streaming of Gezi protests for \u2018harming development of children, youth\u2019]</ref> Members of RT\u00dcK are appointed by the government, and the fines were approved by the 6 AKP members of the 9-member group, against the 3 votes of the opposition.<ref name=\"HDN48712\" /> [[Hayat TV (Turkey)|Hayat TV]], which had also given the protests extensive coverage, was ordered to stop broadcasting on 14 June, although RT\u00dcK reversed its decision in the face of protests.<ref>''[[Radikal]]'', 14 June 2013, [http://www.radikal.com.tr/turkiye/rtuk_hayat_tv_hakkindaki_kapatma_kararini_geri_cekti-1137640 RT\u00dcK, Hayat TV hakk\u0131ndaki kapatma karar\u0131n\u0131 geri \u00e7ekti]</ref>\n* The governor of [[Eski\u015fehir]] sent a threatening e-mail to the journalist [[\u0130smail Saymaz]], over his reports on a Gezi protester's murder in Eski\u015fehir.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/eskisehir-governor-threatens-journalist-over-reports-on-gezi-protesters-murder-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=55547&NewsCatID=341 |title=Eski\u015fehir governor threatens journalist over reports on Gezi protester's murder |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=2011-09-13 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n* Mehmet Barlas, chief editor of the pro-AKP newspaper [[Sabah]] wrote that the CEO of the [[Do\u011fan Holding]] [[Ayd\u0131n Do\u011fan]] should warn his writers who symphathize with Gezi park protesters. A few days later Akif Beki, a pro-AKP columnist started writing for [[H\u00fcrriyet]], Do\u011fan Holding's main newspaper.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/Yazarlar/barlas/2013/09/20/aydin-dogan-yazarlarini-yine-uyarmalidir |title=Ayd\u0131n Do\u011fan yazarlar\u0131n\u0131 yine uyarmal\u0131d\u0131r |author=Mehmet Barlas |newspaper=[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]] |date=20 September 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n* Administration of Sabah newspaper fired its ombudsman Yavuz Baydar, because he criticised newspaper's disinformative approach during Gezi protests.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yavuz Baydar |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/07/baydar-sabah-obudsman-fired-censorship.html |title=Shooting the Arbiter in Turkey: How Sabah Fired Its Ombudsman |newspaper=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=25 July 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Disinformation during protests==\nThe 2013 protests in Turkey witnessed a large amount of disinformation being spread by pro-[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]], [[conservative]], and [[Islamist]] media, also dubbed as ''Yanda\u015f Medya'' (\"Slanted Media\"). Leading newspapers said to be spreading disinformation were ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'', ''[[Yeni Akit]]'', ''[[Daily Sabah]]'', ''[[Star (Turkish newspaper)|Star]]'', ''[[Takvim]]'', ''[[Bug\u00fcn]]'', ''[[Ak\u015fam]]'', ''[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]]'', ''[[T\u00fcrkiye (newspaper)|T\u00fcrkiye]]'', ''[[Milli Gazete]]'', ''[[G\u00fcne\u015f (newspaper)|G\u00fcne\u015f]]'', and ''Milat'', among others. Leading TV channels spreading disinformation were [[Kanal 7]], [[24 (Turkey)|24]], \u00dclke TV, [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation|TRT]], [[Samanyolu TV|Samanyolu]], [[ATV Turkey|ATV]], [[TGRT Haber|TGRT]], [[Sky Turk 360]], TV Net, [[TV8 (Turkey)|TV8]], Beyaz TV, [[Kanalt\u00fcrk]], and Kanal A. Leading internet portals said to be spreading disinformation were Haber 7, Habervaktim, En Son Haber, and Rotahaber.\n* '''June 1:''' Some pro-AKP journalists like Nihal Bengisu Karaca claimed that women in headscarves were being attacked by Gezi protesters. One claimed case in [[Istanbul]]'s [[Kabata\u015f, Istanbul|Kabata\u015f]] district became the center of attention and pro-AKP media claimed that there was security camera footage of the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://haber.stargazete.com/politika/basortulu-anneye-saldirinin-goruntu-kayitlari-mercek-altinda/haber-762399 |title=Ba\u015f\u00f6rt\u00fcl\u00fc anneye sald\u0131r\u0131n\u0131n g\u00f6r\u00fcnt\u00fc kay\u0131tlar\u0131 mercek alt\u0131nda haberi |publisher=[[Star (Turkish newspaper)|Star]] |date=2013-06-14 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> However, the governor of Istanbul said that he didn't see any videos of an attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/istanbul-governor-says-he-didnt-see-any-video-of-attack-on-woman-by-gezi-protesters.aspx?pageID=238&nID=50564&NewsCatID=341 |title=Istanbul Governor says he didn't see any video of attack on woman by Gezi protesters |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=12 July 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> Eight months later, on 14 February 2014, the video was released, showing that there had been no attack on the woman, disproving her and the AKP's claims.<ref name=\"headscarf2014-1\" /><ref name=\"headscarf2014-2\" />\n* '''June 4:''' Pro-AKP newspapers like ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' claimed that protesters who took refuge in [[Dolmabah\u00e7e Mosque]] during a police raid had drunk beer inside the mosque.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/sigindiklari-camide-icki-ictiler-04.06.2013-529113 |title=S\u0131\u011f\u0131nd\u0131klar\u0131 camide i\u00e7ki i\u00e7tiler! |newspaper=[[Yeni \u015eafak]] |date=3 June 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> PM [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] said that they would release security cam videos of this action. However, the [[imam]] of Dolmabah\u00e7e mosque denied those allegations and no videos were ever released to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/pm-erdogan-repeats-previously-denied-reports-of-protesters-entering-mosque-with-shoes-on-.aspx?pageID=238&nid=48520 |title=PM Erdo\u011fan repeats previously denied reports of protesters entering mosque with shoes on |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=9 June 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> Later, the imam of the mosque got assigned to the mosque of a small village on the outskirts of Istanbul.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yasemin \u00c7ongar |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/09/gezi-mosque-alcohol-lie-muezzin-exile.html |title=Turkish Muezzin Who Couldn't Lie Is Exiled |newspaper=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=2013-09-23 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' claimed on the same day that Gezi protesters were preparing for a big provocation and planning to burn the streets an on the holy [[Islam]]ic day of [[Isra and Mi'raj]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/mirac-gecesinde-sokaklari-karistirma-plani-04.06.2013-529279 |title=Mirac gecesinde sokaklar\u0131 kar\u0131\u015ft\u0131rma plan\u0131 |newspaper=[[Yeni \u015eafak]] |date=3 June 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref> ''Yeni \u015eafak'' also claimed that protests were organized by some Turkish advertising agencies and they released an open list of the agencies they accused of organizing the protests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/ajanslar-eyleme-sponsor-04.06.2013-529278?ref=manset-13|title=Ajanslar eyleme sponsor|author=Piri Medya|date=3 June 2013|work=Yeni \u015eafak|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 5:''' Mustafa Durdu, a columnist of the [[Islamic extremism|Islamist extremist]] ''Akit'' newspaper, claimed that protesters may even have performed [[group sex]] inside [[Dolmabah\u00e7e Mosque]].<ref>[http://www.habervaktim.com/yazar/59624/bunlar-cianin-cocuklari.html BUNLAR CIA\u2019n\u0131n \u00c7OCUKLARI - Mustafa Durdu<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225145410/http://www.habervaktim.com/yazar/59624/bunlar-cianin-cocuklari.html |date=December 25, 2014 }}</ref> \nTurkish public broadcasting service TRT aired footage of people burning the Turkish flag. The footage was originally aired in 2010 but featured doctored dates, implying the current demonstrations were somehow secessionist in nature.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ulusalkanal.com.tr/gundem/trtnin-bayrak-yaktilar-videosu-yalan-cikti-h11763.html|title=TRT'nin bayrak yakt\u0131lar videosu yalan \u00e7\u0131kt\u0131!|date = 5 June 2013|newspaper=Ulusalkanal}}</ref>\n* '''June 6:''' Pro-AKP newspapers like ''[[Sabah]]'' reported that the protests were planned by the Serbian civil society organization [[Otpor!]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/Gundem/2013/06/06/gezi-parki-olaylarinin-perde-arkasi|title=Gezi Park\u0131 olaylar\u0131n\u0131n perde arkas\u0131|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/09/gezi-protests-turkey-democratization.html|title=Is Turkey, After Gezi Protests, On Path to Democratization? - Al-Monitor: the Pulse of the Middle East|work=Al-Monitor|accessdate=2 October 2015|date=2013-09-19}}</ref> Pro-AKP newspaper ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' claimed that the Zello mobile app, which was used by protesters to communicate during the protests, was served to them by a source in [[Houston]] and that protesters were taking orders from that source.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/houstondan-olum-emri-06.06.2013-529835?ref=manset-2|title=Houston'dan \u00f6l\u00fcm emri|author=Piri Medya|date=5 June 2013|work=Yeni \u015eafak|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>  \n* '''June 7:''' Police officer Mustafa Sar\u0131 died after falling off a bridge into an underpass while pursuing protesters in [[Adana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/news/turkish-police-officer-bridge-309/|title=Turkish policeman dead after falling from bridge while pursuing protesters|work=RT English|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> However, pro-government media sources like Rotahaber claimed that protesters pushed the police officer from the bridge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://haber.rotahaber.com/gostericilerin-kopruden-attigi-komiser-oldu_374167.html|title=G\u00f6stericilerin k\u00f6pr\u00fcden att\u0131\u011f\u0131 komiser \u00f6ld\u00fc - G\u00fcndem Haberleri - G\u00fcncel Haber - Haber - Spor Haberleri- S\u0131cak haber - Yerel Haber<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> Family of Mustafa Sar\u0131 denied those claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/turkiye/komiser_mustafa_sarinin_ailesi_atilmadi_dustu_iddialar_spekulasyon-1137019|title=Komiser Mustafa Sar\u0131'n\u0131n ailesi: At\u0131lmad\u0131 d\u00fc\u015ft\u00fc, iddialar spek\u00fclasyon|date=6 October 2013|work=Radikal|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 10:''' The newspaper ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' claimed that a theatre play called \"Mi Minor\", allegedly supported by an agency in [[United Kingdom|Britain]], had held rehearsals of \"revolution\" in Turkey for months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-actor-threatened-over-his-gezi-park-support-.aspx?PageID=238&NID=48568&NewsCatID=341|title=Turkish actor threatened over his Gezi Park support - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 12:''' The state-owned [[Anadolu Agency]] provided extensive reporting of protests in London over the [[G8]], and attempted to create a Twitter campaign around the [[hashtag]] #occupylondon, which was picked up by AKP supporters.<ref name=\"HDN48712\">[[Hurriyet Daily News]], 12 June 2013, [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-politicians-slam-foreign-media-coverage-of-the-gezi-park-protests.aspx?pageID=238&nID=48712&NewsCatID=338 Turkish politicians slam foreign media coverage of the Gezi Park protests]</ref>\n* '''June 13:''' The [[Islamism|Islamist]] ''[[Yeni Akit|Akit]]'' newspaper claimed that [[prostitution]] and [[group sex]] was common at Gezi park after 2 am. They based this claim on an \"anonymous journalist who saw this happening with his own eyes and told it to someone else\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.habervaktim.com/haber/330092/kendi-gozlerimle-gordum.html|title=Kendi G\u00f6zlerimle G\u00f6rd\u00fcm|date=13 June 2013|work=Habervaktim|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 14:''' Pro-government [[internet portal]] RotaHaber claimed that a Turkish national working as security chief at the [[United States]] embassy in [[Adana]] was active during protests and that he was an American agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://haber.rotahaber.com/abd-ajani-gezi-parki-eyleminde_376418.html#ixzz2lJqmZZg3|title=ABD ajan\u0131 Gezi Park\u0131 eyleminde...! - G\u00fcndem Haberleri - G\u00fcncel Haber - Haber - Spor Haberleri- S\u0131cak haber - Yerel Haber<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n* '''June 15:''' ''[[Yeni Akit|Akit]]'' accused supermarket chain [[Migros]] of delivering free supplies to the protesters at Gezi park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.habervaktim.com/haber/330233/eylemcileri-migros-besliyor.html|title=Eylemcileri Migros Besliyor|date=14 June 2013|work=Habervaktim|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> However, goods delivered to the park were bought by protesters through supermarket's internet shop.\n* '''June 18:''' After the clearing of Gezi Park camp, [[Erdem G\u00fcnd\u00fcz]] started the Standing Man/Woman protest that spread to all over Turkey. Pro-AKP newspapers claimed that standing protest is a [[CIA]] tactic from their handbook for non-violent action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://haber.stargazete.com/guncel/duran-adam-eylemi-cia-taktigi-cikti/haber-763641|title=Duran Adam Eylemi CIA Takti\u011fi \u00c7\u0131kt\u0131!|work=Star.com.tr|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> \n[[Takvim]] newspaper devoted its front page to a fake \"interview\" with [[CNN]]'s [[Christiane Amanpour]], in which Amanpour supposedly confesses that CNN's coverage of the protests was motivated by \"the express interest of destabilizing Turkey for international business interests\". The paper included a small disclaimer on the 14th page, saying \"This interview is not real, but what you will read here is real.\"<ref>{{ cite news | url = http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-daily-defames-cnn-anchor-christiane-amanpour.aspx?pageID=238&nID=49022&NewsCatID=341 | title = 'Shame on you,' Amanpour reacts to Turkish daily that published fake interview | date = 18 June 2013 | accessdate = 14 February 2014 | newspaper = [[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] }}</ref> Takvim newspaper also sued Amanpour.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/18/christiane-amanpour-takvim-turkish-newspaper_n_3460023.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Katherine | last=Fung | title=Christiane Amanpour Slams Turkish Newspaper For Fake Interview | date=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n* '''June 18:''' Pro-AKP [[internet portal]] Haber 7 claimed that during the first days of the protests, anti-government protesters were planning a civilian [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] by occupying PM [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]'s [[Ankara]] home and [[Istanbul]] office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haber7.com/guncel/haber/1041088-basbakan-erdoganin-evine-3-bin-kisiyle-baskin|title=Ba\u015fbakan Erdo\u011fan'\u0131n evine 3 bin ki\u015fiyle bask\u0131n|date=21 June 2013|work=Haber7|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 24:''' During one of the public forums in [[Istanbul]], which was televised live on Halk TV, a protester said that maybe they should wear police uniforms to protest police brutality. Pro-AKP media sources like ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' served this as \"Halk TV is planning a provocation by telling protesters to wear police uniforms and make false flag attacks\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/polis-degilsen-kiyafet-alamazsin-25.06.2013-535270|title=Polis de\u011filsen k\u0131yafet alamazs\u0131n|author=Piri Medya|date=24 June 2013|work=Yeni \u015eafak|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''June 27:''' Ethem Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck was shot dead by a police officer during the protests in [[Ankara]]. Pro-AKP newspapers released pictures of Ethem Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck holding an assault rifle and claimed that he was the member of a [[terrorist]] organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haber7.com/guncel/haber/1043150-sarisulukle-ilgili-cok-tartisilan-fotograf|title=Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck'le ilgili \u00e7ok tart\u0131\u015f\u0131lan foto\u011fraf!|date=27 June 2013|work=Haber7|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> However, later it was found out that those pictures were taken when Ethem Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck was working as a laborer for the construction of a military post.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.radikal.com.tr/turkiye/ethem_sarisulukun_fotografi_kampta_degil_karakolda_cekilmis-1139428 | title = Ethem Sar\u0131s\u00fcl\u00fck'\u00fcn foto\u011fraf\u0131 kampta de\u011fil karakolda \u00e7ekilmi\u015f | date = 27 June 2013 | accessdate = 14 February 2014 | newspaper = [[Radikal]] | last = Dursun | first = Ay\u015feg\u00fcl }}</ref>\n* '''July 22:''' Pro-AKP businessman Zeynel Abidin Erdem claimed that some source in [[Mexico]] bought 600 pizzas for the gezi park protesters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazete5.com/haber/gezi-parki-na-600-pizza-siparisi-hangi-ulkeden-odendi-347757|title=Gezi Park\u0131'na 600 pizza sipari\u015fi hangi \u00fclkeden \u00f6dendi?|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> \n* '''August 24:''' The Islamist ''[[Yeni Akit|Akit]]'' newspaper claimed that Gezi protesters were preparing for a big provocation on the August 30 Victory Day celebrations.<ref>[http://www.habervaktim.com/haber/340105/geziciler-30-agustosta-provokasyona-hazirlaniyor.html Geziciler 30 A\u011fustos\u2019ta Provokasyona Haz\u0131rlan\u0131yor<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225145414/http://www.habervaktim.com/haber/340105/geziciler-30-agustosta-provokasyona-hazirlaniyor.html |date=December 25, 2014 }}</ref>\n* '''August 26:''' World famous linguist and activist [[Noam Chomsky]] accused the pro-government ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' newspaper of fabricating some parts of an interview that was done with him via [[email]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/chomsky-accuses-turkish-daily-of-fabricating-parts-of-interview.aspx?pageID=238&nID=53554&NewsCatID=341|title=Chomsky accuses Turkish daily of fabricating parts of interview - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> The administration of ''Yeni \u015eafak'' denied this allegation and promised to release the original English content of emails. However, the released content was full of grammatical mistakes. Later it was found out that ''Yeni \u015eafak'' used the [[Google Translate]] service to translate fabricated Turkish content to English and served that as the original interview.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://blogs.wsj.com/emergingeurope/2013/09/05/turkish-newspapers-fake-chomsky-interview-lost-in-translation/ | work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> After grammatical errors, particularly \"milk port\" became a sensation at social media, ''Yeni \u015eafak'' finally admitted some parts were fabricated and removed the interview from its web site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-daily-admits-to-making-up-parts-of-chomsky-interview-releases-alleged-text-.aspx?PageID=238&NID=53617&NewsCatID=341|title=Turkish daily admits to making up parts of Chomsky interview, releases alleged text - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-daily-apologizes-for-fabricated-chomsky-interview.aspx?pageID=238&nID=53668&NewsCatID=341|title=Turkish daily apologizes for fabricated Chomsky interview - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''September 9:''' [[\u0130stanbul]] was a candidate for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]], but lost out to [[Tokyo]]. Pro-AKP media and government officials blamed Gezi protesters of conspiring internationally so that \u0130stanbul would lose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/world/europe/turkish-officials-blame-protesters-for-failed-olympics-bid|title=Turkish officials blame protesters for failed Olympics bid|author=Thomas Seibert|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> \n* '''September 28:''' Beyaz TV, which is owned by the son of the mayor of [[Ankara]], aired a program showing a 13-year-old child who claimed that he was paid by Gezi park protesters to throw stones at the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yenisafak.com.tr/gundem-haber/tas-atmak-5-tl-tomanin-onune-yatmak-10-tl-27.09.2013-569124|title=Ta\u015f atmak 5 TOMA'n\u0131n \u00f6n\u00fcne yatmak 10 TL|author=Piri Medya|date=27 September 2013|work=Yeni \u015eafak|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> The child also said that \"protestors were probably drinking cat blood at the Gezi park\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yurtgazetesi.com.tr/gundem/gezide-kedi-kani-iciyorlardi-h42479.html|title=Gezi'de kedi kan\u0131 i\u00e7iyorlard\u0131|date=29 September 2013|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''October:''' During autumn, [[Istanbul]] witnessed long traffic jams. Pro-AKP journalists accused Gezi protesters of deliberately causing traffic jams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gundem.milliyet.com.tr/trafik-lobisinin-isi-mi-/gundem/detay/1776162/default.htm|title=Trafik lobisinin i\u015fi mi?|date=11 October 2013|work=MILLIYET HABER - T\u00dcRKIYE'NIN HABER SITESI|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> \n* '''November 3:''' The day after the grand opening of [[Marmaray]] project, many technical problems occurred.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/marmaray-calm-on-second-day-after-first-days-storm-of-technical-problems.aspx?pageID=238&nID=57176&NewsCatID=341|title=Marmaray calm on second day after first day's storm of technical problems - LOCAL|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> Pro-AKP T\u00fcrkiye newspaper accused Gezi protesters of delibaretly sabotaging Marmaray.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turkiyegazetesi.com.tr/gundem/97567.aspx|title=Marmaray'a gezi sabotaj\u0131|author=turkiyegazetesi editor|date=3 November 2013|work=turkiyegazetesi.com.tr|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''November 20:''' The pro-AKP ''[[Takvim]]'' newspaper, which printed a fabricated interview with [[CNN]]'s [[Christiane Amanpour]], claimed that seven Turkish Jewish citizens who did their military service in [[Israel]] were agents of [[Mossad]] and they were the leaders of Gezi protests. The newspaper also accused [[CNN]] and [[BBC]] of being part of \"this dirty plan\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takvim.com.tr/Guncel/2013/11/20/mossad-gezisi|title=Mossad Gezi'si|work=takvim.com.tr|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n* '''February 14:''' Months after the end of the protests, video footage revealed that there had in fact been no attack on a woman wearing a [[headscarf]] by protesters on June 1. The woman and Prime Minister Erdo\u011fan had claimed in press conferences and political rallies that protesters had attacked her and her baby.<ref name=\"headscarf2014-1\">{{cite news | title = Released footage shows no physical attack on headscarf-wearing woman during Gezi protests | url = http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/163179/released-footage-shows-no-physical-attack-on-headscarf-wearing-woman-during-gezi-protests.html | date = 14 February 2014 | newspaper = Turkish Weekly }}</ref><ref name=\"headscarf2014-2\">{{cite news | title = Video casts doubt over alleged attack on headscarved woman | url = http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2014/Feb-14/247358-video-casts-doubt-over-alleged-attack-on-headscarved-woman.ashx | date = 14 February 2014 | newspaper = [[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]] }}</ref>\n* '''July 14:''' Pro-AKP ''[[Yeni \u015eafak]]'' released an article titled \"The Horrible Istanbul Plan of Gezi Protestors\" on their internet portal. The article claimed that Gezi protesters are conspiring to undermine the AKP government by wasting water in order to empty the dams supplying \u0130stanbul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/national_pro-govt-media-gezi-protesters-conspiring-to-use-up-istanbuls-water_353227.html|title=Pro-gov't media: Gezi protesters conspiring to use up \u0130stanbul's water|date=16 July 2014|work=TodaysZaman|accessdate=2 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818200817/http://www.todayszaman.com/national_pro-govt-media-gezi-protesters-conspiring-to-use-up-istanbuls-water_353227.html|archivedate=18 August 2015|df=}}</ref> After the article became a source of mocking nationwide, Yeni \u015eafak removed the article from their web site.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Backward Run]]'' ([[Turkish language|Tr]]: ''Tornistan'') a Turkish animated short film about media censorship during the 2013 protests<ref>{{cite news  |  title = Tornistan: Turkey's summer of anti-government protests | first = Nabeelah | last = Shabbir | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/mar/11/tornistan-turkey-animated-film-gezi-park | date= 2014-03-11 | accessdate= 2014-07-07 | publisher = [[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Disinformation}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Media censorship and disinformation during the 2013-14 protests in Turkey}}\n[[Category:Censorship in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Media freedom in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Gezi Park protests]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: symphathize \u2192 sympathize", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media_censorship_and_disinformation_during_the_Gezi_Park_protests"}
